              <span id="reviewTextContainer3819145842" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7043191542344912711"><b>3.5 stars</b><br/><br/><i>***Historical Hellions Book Club | February 2021 Selection***</i><br/><br/>Regency <i>Mr. &amp; Mrs. Smith</i> without the espionage and explosion—just two hot-headed hero / heroine testing each other&apos;s tolerance in a marriage of convenience. <b><i>Love Only Once</i> is all-out soap opera theatrics with no subtlety, and sometimes unabashedly ridiculous; no substance, but one can&apos;t deny the entertainment value in this old-school historical romance.</b><br/><br/><i>**Minor spoiler ahead**</i><br/><br/>While it&apos;s common to have a hardheaded, womanizing r</span>
  <span id="freeText7043191542344912711" style="display:none"><b>3.5 stars</b><br /><br /><i>***Historical Hellions Book Club | February 2021 Selection***</i><br /><br />Regency <i>Mr. &amp; Mrs. Smith</i> without the espionage and explosion—just two hot-headed hero / heroine testing each other's tolerance in a marriage of convenience. <b><i>Love Only Once</i> is all-out soap opera theatrics with no subtlety, and sometimes unabashedly ridiculous; no substance, but one can't deny the entertainment value in this old-school historical romance.</b><br /><br /><i>**Minor spoiler ahead**</i><br /><br />While it's common to have a hardheaded, womanizing rake as the hero, it's quite refreshing to have a heroine at equal footing, who's just as brutal and headstrong. Even with the immediate physical attraction, the hijinks commenced with the heroine trying to maintain their untimely marriage, while the hero trying his hardest to escape. The motivation behind the turmoil is head-scratchingly banal (she wanted her over-protective uncles to stop meddling with her life, he was self-conscious about his illegitimate origin), resulting in the pairing coming across more like two spoiled children rather than sharp-witted adults, but the fiery chemistry is appealing, and the back and forth sneering captivating.<br /><br />As the first book in an eventual 12 books series, the foundation is clearly laid for future expansion, <u>to the point of distraction</u>. A massive amount of family members was introduced at plot-stopping speed, with many divergence into side character backstories that are only tangentially related to the main plot. Some historical romances are able to interweave this gracefully, but in this instance the intention to build up characters for subsequent books makes for a chaotic story progression.<br /><br />While not enjoyment-breaking, <i>Love Only Once</i> definitely shows its 30+ age with some of its depiction, which can be read as less than tasteful by today's standard; some creeping on the verge of abuse (sexual intercourse with a partner who was deliberately made dead drunk—the book DID emphasize it was desirable for both), and others I'm at complete at a loss with its intention (the unconscious breast feeding scene... was it suppose to be funny?!). Overall I chose to approach these as an artifact of its time, accepting them at face value and not trying to over-analyze, but just be aware these borderline instances do exist.<br /><br /><i>**Minor spoiler ends**</i><br /><br />Leave this behind if you're seeking deep character development or profound discussion, <i>Love Only Once</i> is <u>as enjoyable as trashy movies you watch and forget—pure sensory stimulation and not much else</u>. With its snarky leads, equally hot-tempered family members, and abundance of misunderstanding, it at least succeeds in perking my interest in checking out the remaining books in the series.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7043191542344912711" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


