<div id="review_643060261" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/643060261" />
    <a title="Tiera McMillian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21366500-tiera-mcmillian"><img alt="Tiera McMillian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1547743777p2/21366500.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/643060261?book_show_action=true">Jun 16, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tiera McMillian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tiera McMillian" href="/user/show/21366500-tiera-mcmillian">Tiera McMillian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21366500-tiera-mcmillian?shelf=march2020">march2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer643060261" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6821642851120222469">*Reread Review* <br/>If I could post a picture of my actual copy of this book you would be amazed. The cover is falling off and all the pages are a yellow/orange color from age. I&apos;m pretty sure I&apos;ve owned it since I was 17 years old which is about 1/2 of my life. So just some history of me and Johanna Lindsey.. She has over the years been one of my most favorite author&apos;s. One of the things that had nothing to do with the actual writing, that I loved about her books was that despite the original bodic</span>
  <span id="freeText6821642851120222469" style="display:none">*Reread Review* <br />If I could post a picture of my actual copy of this book you would be amazed. The cover is falling off and all the pages are a yellow/orange color from age. I'm pretty sure I've owned it since I was 17 years old which is about 1/2 of my life. So just some history of me and Johanna Lindsey.. She has over the years been one of my most favorite author's. One of the things that had nothing to do with the actual writing, that I loved about her books was that despite the original bodice ripper cover the authors started putting just random landscape pictures on the covers. This allowed me to be able to carry it around in public and not get ribbed for the fabiotastic cover. This was greatly appreciated by me back in the day lol. Back in the day (wink) books weren't as easily accessed as they are now so it took me years to be able to get this whole series in my possession and then of course as the years progressed new books would come out making my series incomplete once again. It is devastating to know that there will be no more books forthcoming due to her passing last year my heart goes out to her family and all her other readers.<br /><br />This book starts it all off as we are introduced to the Mallory brood. Starting with Regina was great because it allowed us to meet the entire family and allowed the author to start all of their stories without the reader even being aware that this was happening. I find that author's deemed "great" in the 80s and 90s tended to keep up their status quo. You won't find rushed plots or unbuilt worlds in anything written by these author's. All the characters will be fleshed out to the max and you also don't see POVs like you see so very often in todays books. The author seamlessly moves back and forth between the minds of the characters so there is no divide of chapters or breaks to switch viewpoints. This is something that took me a while to get into as I started reading newer author's works. I couldn't understand why all this switching back and forth had to occur because this is what I was weened on, this seamless exchange between all the characters. Even the underlings aren't ignored.<br /><br />During my reread I also found yet another thing that I'm very appreciative of in Johanna's writing style. Her ability to remain in time period and in character even during the character's thoughts. You are completely immersed at all times in the story, in the past, in the romance. Yes the behavior of the characters, especially our males in these series, is archaic and barbaric. I know there are times when even I get a little eye rolley by some of the things going on but thats the way it used to be. Some women don't really like to be reminded of the way we were treated in the past but it doesn't bother me much. The amount of research needed to accurately put together a historical novel, not based on someones true life events, is actually pretty astounding. <br /><br />I'm leaving my 5 star rating. Just the sight of my poor book after all these years is evidence enough to me that it is an amazing read. That and the fact that I've probably read it dozens of times. No lie I used to reread them every year. Now with such easy access to all kinds of new stuff I don't come back as often as I used to, but I'm glad I came back for this series and its reread. I'm tempted to try some of these in audio but I'm also scared to death to not like them as much. We will see. Amazing start to the series!<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6821642851120222469" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


